# Components

Components are reusable building blocks for your pages.

## Creating a Component

Create a V file in the `components/` directory:

```v
// components/callout.v
module components

pub struct Callout {
pub:
    type_   string  // info, warning, success, error
    content string
}

pub fn (c Callout) render() string {
    icon := match c.type_ {
        'info' { 'üí°' }
        'warning' { '‚ö†Ô∏è' }
        'success' { '‚úÖ' }
        'error' { 'üö®' }
        else { '‚Ñπ' }
    }
    return '<div class="callout callout-${c.type_}">
        <span class="callout-icon">${icon}</span>
        <div class="callout-content">${c.content}</div>
    </div>'
}
```

## Using Components

Use components in your `.vdx` files with HTML-like syntax:

```html
<Callout type_="info">
This is an informational message.
</Callout>
```

<Callout type_="warning">
Use `type_` with underscore because `type` is a reserved keyword in V.
</Callout>

## Component Props

Props are passed as attributes. In your component struct, define public fields:

```v
pub struct MyComponent {
pub:
    size    string = 'medium'  // Default value
    variant string = 'default'
    content string             // Children content
}
```

Then use in your `.vdx`:

```html
<MyComponent size="large" variant="primary">
Content goes here
</MyComponent>
```

## Built-in Components

Velt projects come with these components:

| Component | Description | Props |
|-----------|-------------|-------|
| `Callout` | Alert boxes with icons | `type_`: info, warning, success, error |
| `Hero` | Hero section for landing pages | `title`, `subtitle` |

## Children Content

Content between tags becomes the `content` field:

```html
<Callout type_="info">
This text becomes the content field.
</Callout>
```

The content is automatically parsed as Markdown.

## Creating Custom Components

Here's a complete example of a custom component:

```v
// components/feature_card.v
module components

pub struct FeatureCard {
pub:
    icon    string
    title   string
    content string
}

pub fn (f FeatureCard) render() string {
    return '<div class="feature-card">
        <span class="feature-icon">${f.icon}</span>
        <h3>${f.title}</h3>
        <p>${f.content}</p>
    </div>'
}
```

Use it:

```html
<FeatureCard icon="üöÄ" title="Fast">
Blazingly fast builds with V.
</FeatureCard>
```
